wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"https://alphaomegadigital.com.au/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/invitefriends-1024x453.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-7649\"/><figcaption>Don\'t forget to invite your friends to like your page. Facebook will auto populate your friends list, and you can also add anyone by inviting them on email. </figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Want to gain some traction?</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You have successfully setup your Facebook page. A hundred of your friends liked it. Cool. But what next? I strongly advise the following steps to build your page followers and network amongst other businesses</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>1. Google your area - suburb, municipality, town (each of these will usually have a seperate page) and join the groups. Don\'t post until you read the group rules. For example my town group has a rule that businesses can only promote themselves on Wednesdays. This is to keep the group focused on community issues, and ensure it\'s not one big giant business spam. Take advantage of this opportunity to spruik yourself and stick to the self promotion guidelines. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>2. Create a Facebook group and be the admin. Post helpful content.   Genuinely try and help people. Admin it properly, and make sure people behave and adhere to facebooks anti bullying guidelines. Make the group name general, such as \"marketing help for small businesses.\" Stay away from memes and cat videos. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>3. Setup a Facebook advertising schedule to promote your free group. Set your budget at $3 a day. Continue to provide value and post helpful content, and don\'t forget to answer questions. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>4. Use an auto publishing blog to social tool such as <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/blog2social/\">blog2social</a> or <a href=\"https://ifttt.com/\">IFTTT. </a>This saves you copying and pasting blog URL\'s to your social channels, and also makes sure you don\'t forget to do it.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>5. Network with other complementary businesses in your area. Like and follow their pages, and private message them to see if you can work together. Focus on the ones that respond and are open to the idea, and accept that some wont be. Organise coffee with the ones that are keen, and get some face to face time with them. You have a much greater chance of closing a deal face to face than you do online. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There is so much more I would write on this topic, but for now let\'s leave it at that! I will be writing more posts about Facebook advertising, getting email subscribers and optimising ad campaigns so be sure to check those out when they\'re featured on the blog. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Did you set this up? How did you go? Be sure to reach out and let me know if you found this setup process easy. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','A step by step guide to setting up your Facebook business page, and growing it.','','inherit','closed','closed','','7324-revision-v1','','','2020-08-05 04:55:10','2020-08-05 04:55:10','',7324,'https://alphaomegadigital.com.au/7324-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(7654,1,'2020-08-05 05:29:15','2020-08-05 05:29:15','{\n    \"blogdescription\": {\n        \"value\": \"a complete marketing system\",\n        \"type\": \"option\",\n        \"user_id\": 1,\n        \"date_modified_gmt\": \"2020-08-05 05:29:15\"\n    }\n}','','','trash','closed','closed','','02661fe7-cf7a-40e5-b4b8-8b3469b61f32','','','2020-08-05 05:29:15','2020-08-05 05:29:15','',0,'http://alphaomegadigital.com.au/02661fe7-cf7a-40e5-b4b8-8b3469b61f32/',0,'customize_changeset','',0),(7655,1,'2020-08-05 05:29:45','2020-08-05 05:29:45','http://alphaomegadigital.com.au/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/cropped-alpha-and-omega-white-white-150ppi-2.png','cropped-alpha-and-omega-white-white-150ppi-2.png','','inherit','open','closed','','cropped-alpha-and-omega-white-white-150ppi-2-png','','','2020-08-05 05:29:45','2020-08-05 05:29:45','',0,'http://alphaomegadigital.com.au/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/cropped-alpha-and-omega-white-white-150ppi-2.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(7656,1,'2020-08-05 05:29:49','2020-08-05 05:29:49','{\n    \"site_icon\": {\n        \"value\": 7655,\n        \"type\": \"option\",\n        \"user_id\": 1,\n        \"date_modified_gmt\": \"2020-08-05 05:29:49\"\n    }\n}','','','trash','closed','closed','','34f97599-33d2-474f-9810-d14de00863b4','','','2020-08-05 05:29:49','2020-08-05 05:29:49','',0,'http://alphaomegadigital.com.au/34f97599-33d2-474f-9810-d14de00863b4/',0,'customize_changeset','',0),(7657,1,'2020-08-05 05:33:16','2020-08-05 05:33:16','{\n    \"genesis-settings[header_scripts]\": {\n        \"value\": \"<!-- Global site tag (gtag.js) - Google Analytics -->\\n<script async src=\\\"https://www.googletagmanager.com/gtag/js?id=UA-174569193-1\\\"></script>\\n<script>\\n  window.dataLayer = window.dataLayer || [];\\n  function gtag(){dataLayer.push(arguments);}\\n  gtag(\'js\', new Date());\\n\\n  gtag(\'config\', \'UA-174569193-1\');\\n</script>\",\n        \"type\": \"option\",\n        \"user_id\": 1,\n        \"date_modified_gmt\": \"2020-08-05 05:33:16\"\n    }\n}','','','trash','closed','closed','','30d5b68b-1d9a-4d6b-8ad3-a3dc73603c7f','','','2020-08-05 05:33:16','2020-08-05 05:33:16','',0,'http://alphaomegadigital.com.au/30d5b68b-1d9a-4d6b-8ad3-a3dc73603c7f/',0,'customize_changeset','',0),(7658,1,'2020-08-05 05:36:10','2020-08-05 05:36:10','','genesis-icon-600x600','','inherit','open','closed','','genesis-icon-600x600','','','2020-08-05 05:36:19','2020-08-05 05:36:19','',7478,'http://alphaomegadigital.com.au/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/genesis-icon-600x600-1.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(7659,1,'2020-08-05 05:36:28','2020-08-05 05:36:28','<!-- wp:image {\"id\":7658,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://alphaomegadigital.com.au/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/genesis-icon-600x600-1.png\" alt=\"Genesis Framework image\" class=\"wp-image-7658\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>1. It has a high coding standard and is very well maintained.</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"textColor\":\"black\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-black-color has-text-color\">Each release of Genesis solves not only bug fixes and compile errors that the development team have found, but also new features requested by the genesis community to make building web projects with Genesis easier. New releases of Genesis range from every few months to daily. You can view the changelog <strong><a href=\"https://studiopress.github.io/genesis/changelog/\">here</a>.</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"textColor\":\"black\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-black-color has-text-color\">From a professional standpoint, I know that when I run into development problems with Genesis, I have a variety of support options available. Those options range from logging a ticket with <a href=\"https://www.studiopress.com/\"><strong>Studiopress</strong></a>, starting a thread in the community <strong><a href=\"https://genesis.community/\">forum</a>,</strong> or even reaching out to my personal mentor <a href=\"https://www.billerickson.net/\"><strong>Bill Erickson</strong></a> who is arguably one of the best Genesis developers out there.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>2. Its easier to keep your site updated</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>So a lot of agencies in Australia and around the world, pride themselves on building Wordpress websites from scratch. To clarify, from scratch means using bare bones starter theme like<a href=\"https://github.com/wpbones/WPBones\"> BonesWP</a> or Automattics <a href=\"https://underscores.me/\">underscores</a> theme. It could also be your own customised starter theme such as Bill Erickson\'s <a href=\"https://github.com/billerickson/ea-genesis-child\">genesis child</a>. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now there are huge pros and cons to both development strategies, and sometimes using an existing child theme to build a site with a lot of custom functions and plugins is like trying to squash a square peg into a round hole. In these cases, then no doubt a custom theme is required. And the project cost is definitely reflective of the amount of work done. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>However, if you build a custom site then you need to be prepared for ongoing costs to maintain the site in the form of debugging and code updates. Because in a nutshell, a custom theme that is not maintained is essential a deprecated web app, and there are going to be issues over time. You wouldn\'t refuse to update the ios on your phone now would you? </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You should apply the same mentality to a custom site build. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For small businesses and smaller budget projects, having the Genesis parent theme updated regularly squashes a lot of these issues, and means a business without much of an ongoing maintenance budget can have an update site with each Genesis release. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>3. There are many ways to skin the genesis cat</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The term \"Wordpress development\" can encompass many things, from customising existing child themes, building a starter theme, building plugins, maintaining plugins and so on. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>And within the first category you can build a website with:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>no code using an extensions such as the <a href=\"https://www.wpbeaverbuilder.com/\">Beaver Builder</a></li><li>you can use and modify a purchased Genesis child theme by altering the stylesheet and functions.php file</li><li>you can use the Genesis <a href=\"https://github.com/studiopress/genesis-sample\">sample</a> theme and import the demo content as a base</li><li> or use your own starter theme</li><li>You can build a site with Gutenberg and style the blocks</li><li>You can call in a variety of widget areas and use raw html </li><li>You can use Genesis simple hooks to hook in your markup to specific areas </li><li>You can create custom blocks with ACF and style them in SCSS. </li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This list isn\'t exhaustive, and I\'m sure there are cross combinations of these that can be applied too. The point here, is that Genesis is accessible to people from all levels of experience, and there are options for you even if you\'re just starting out. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>4. There are Genesis dedicated extension plugins to help you</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Whether you are a seasoned developer who wants to save time or a newbie who is less comfortable editing your functions.php file, there are an array of Genesis plugins with additional functionality to make your development process feature rich without a lot of effort. Studiopress has a library of plugins you can checkout <a href=\"https://www.studiopress.com/plugins/\">here</a>. Certainly, starting out the Genesis simple hooks plugin certainly assisted in learning which actions and filter hooks applied to each page section, and that has been incredibly helpful. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>5. Its easier to use Genesis for all your projects than jump around from one them to another</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The phone call that fills me with dread is the one where a client has a third party theme and page builder that was used to build their site, and now they want changes to their site. Ugh. Every theme is built so differently, and it can take you a whole day to get your head around how the site was built and figure out the file ecosystem. Plus some third party page builders are horribly slow and very limited in functionality. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This is a problem because website changes are usually a small job, but suddenly the client wants functions and customisations that aren\'t possible with their current setup. So I then find myself explaining it will cost significantly more, and usually we end up looping back to the available functions and making compromises to get the result. This all adds to unforeseen development hours, and at this stage I haven\'t made any money on this job, and both the client and myself are unhappy. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Staying with one framework like Genesis, means you get to know the ecosystem and whether it is built this way or that, you are familiar and can make changes fairly easily without pulling your hair out. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Why I use the Genesis Framework','','inherit','closed','closed','','7478-revision-v1','','','2020-08-05 05:36:28','2020-08-05 05:36:28','',7478,'https://alphaomegadigital.com.au/7478-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(7664,1,'2020-08-05 05:56:21','2020-08-05 05:56:21','<!-- wp:image {\"id\":7658,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://alphaomegadigital.com.au/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/genesis-icon-600x600-1.png\" alt=\"Genesis Framework image\" class=\"wp-image-7658\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>1. It has a high coding standard and is very well maintained.</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"textColor\":\"black\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-black-color has-text-color\">Each